x": 4}, {"url": "http://www.gwleibniz.com/leibniz_house/leibniz_house.html", "anchor_text": "folding chair", "paragraph_index": 4}, {"url": "https://www.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/mathematical-treasure-leibnizs-papers-on-calculus", "anchor_text": "three most famous articles", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calculus", "anchor_text": "Calculus", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acta_Eruditorum", "anchor_text": "Acta Eruditorum", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://math.berkeley.edu/~robin/Leibniz/work.html", "anchor_text": "transmutation theorem", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_by_parts", "anchor_text": "integration by parts", "paragraph_index": 8}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Summa", "anchor_text": "summa", "paragraph_index": 12}, {"url": "http://web.csulb.edu/~rmena/", "anchor_text": "Mena", "paragraph_index": 17}, {"url": "https://books.google.com.br/books?id=QnXSqvTiEjYC&dq=calculus+gallery+dunham&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjz1rHMqpPpAhU7HrkGHTdcBaQQ6AEIKDAA", "anchor_text": "performing some simple algebra", "paragraph_index": 19}, {"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_by_parts", "anchor_text": "integration by parts", "paragraph_index": 23}, {"url": "https://github.com/marcotav", "anchor_text": "Github", "paragraph_index": 25}, {"url": "https://marcotavora.me/", "anchor_text": "www.marcotavora.me", "paragraph_index": 25}], "all_paragraphs": ["Modern calculus, which can be defined as \u201cthe mathematical study of continuous change,\u201d was developed independently by two of the great thinkers of the 17th and 18th centuries, namely, Isaac Newton and Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz.", "In this article, my focus will be on the work of Leibniz, and I will show, based mainly on the analysis in Dunham and Mena, how he derived the well-known formula for the integration by parts.", "For an article about Isaac Newton\u2019s early mathematical achievements, see the link below.", "Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz was the quintessential polymath. He made fundamental contributions to a broad range of topics, including philosophy, mathematics, linguistics, theology, engineering, jurisprudence, law, computer science, and geology. Leibniz once remarked that he often needed to use a substantial part of his week to document the thoughts of just a single morning (for an outstanding biography of Leibniz, see Antognazza).", "Below, on the left, is a picture of his working space in his last residence in Hannover. On the right, the folding chair that he took with him when he traveled.", "The titles of the three most famous articles on the Calculus that Leibniz published in the first scientific journal of German-speaking Europe, the Acta Eruditorum were:", "In English, the titles are, respectively:", "The title pages are shown in Fig. 3 below.", "The goal of this article is to show that a particular case of Leibniz\u2019s transmutation theorem (see the explanation of this peculiar title below) gives us the famous formula for the integration by parts.", "The transmutation theorem is about finding areas between curves. To understand Leibniz\u2019s rationale, consider Figs. 4 and 5 and let us follow Leibniz\u2019s strategy to calculate the area beneath the curve AB (or equivalently, between the curves y=0 and the curve AB).", "Leibniz considered the total area to be the sum of areas with infinitesimal base dx:", "Now consider Fig. 5 below and the infinitesimal rectangle with base dx (note that dx in the figure is not to scale). Its area is y dx. Since the area below the curve is the sum of the areas of all rectangles, Leibniz chose the well-known notation to indicate the total area:", "The sign or symbol \u222b is an elongated S that stands for the word \u201csum\u201d (more precisely, the Latin summa).", "From Leibniz\u2019s construction in Fig. 5, the following relation holds:", "Fig. 6 shows part of Fig. 5. From it, we see that the angle WOT is \u03b1, which makes the triangles \u0394OTW and the infinitesimal triangle similar. As a consequence we obtain:", "Since the base and height of the triangle \u0394OPQ (see Fig. 5) are respectively ds and h, its area is, using Eq. 4, given by:", "Hence, the total area of the wedge from A to B is given by the following integral:", "The final step is to find a relation between the area beneath the curve AB and the area of the wedge. Fig. 5 shows that (see Mena for details):", "Hence, the area beneath the curve AB is \u201ctransmuted\u201d into the sum of two parts, namely, the area of the wedge and the difference", "Using Eqs. 3 and 7 (and performing some simple algebra), we obtain:", "Now consider Fig. 6. We see that:", "If we now make the following choices:", "and substitute these definitions in Eq. 9 we get:", "We see that, quite unexpectedly, the convoluted construction in Fig. 5 gives us one of the most used formulae from calculus, the integration by parts!", "Thanks for reading and see you soon! As always, constructive criticism and feedback are always welcome!", "My Github and personal website www.marcotavora.me have some other interesting material both about mathematics and other topics such as physics, data science, and finance. Check them out!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Theoretical physicist, data scientist, and scientific writer."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F5ee1e485a5a2&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fthe-calculus-according-to-leibniz-5ee1e485a5a2&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "h